    slug: "ghar-barbaad-kue-hotay-hein",
    description: `Ghar Barbaad Kue Hotay Hein is an Urdu-language Islamic book that addresses the causes and consequences of household destruction and family breakdown from an Islamic perspective. The title, which translates roughly to "Why Homes Get Destroyed," immediately signals the book's focus on a problem that affects countless families across Muslim communities — the disintegration of the family unit through conflict, neglect, misunderstanding, and the abandonment of Islamic principles in domestic life. The book draws upon Quranic injunctions, prophetic hadith, and the accumulated wisdom of Islamic scholarship to identify the root causes of family problems and to offer practical, faith-based solutions that can help families prevent or repair the damage that threatens their homes.

The book begins by establishing the Islamic framework for the family, presenting marriage and the household as sacred institutions that are fundamental to the health of society and the preservation of faith. It discusses the Quranic description of marriage as a relationship of "tranquility, mercy, and love" (Surah Ar-Rum: 21) and the hadith in which the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) declared the family as the foundation of a person's happiness in this world. Against this ideal, the book then catalogues the specific behaviors, attitudes, and sins that contribute to the destruction of homes: domestic violence, infidelity, financial irresponsibility, disrespect toward in-laws, interference from extended family, the neglect of marital rights, addiction, and the failure to communicate openly and honestly between spouses.

Each chapter of the book is dedicated to a specific cause of household breakdown, presenting the problem, its Islamic ruling, relevant Quranic verses and hadith, and practical advice for addressing it. The author draws upon real-life examples and case studies (with identities anonymized) to illustrate how seemingly small issues can escalate into major crises when they are left unaddressed. The book places particular emphasis on the role of ego (nafs), jealousy, suspicion, and the failure to follow the Islamic guidelines for resolving disputes — including the Quranic command to appoint arbiters from both families when a marital conflict reaches a serious level. The Urdu prose is straightforward and compassionate, avoiding harsh judgment while remaining clear about what Islam permits and prohibits in domestic matters. This book is aimed at married couples, engaged individuals, parents, and anyone involved in family counseling or conflict resolution within the Muslim community. It serves both as a preventive guide that helps families identify and address problems before they become destructive, and as a resource for those who are already experiencing difficulties and need practical, Islamic guidance on how to navigate them.`,
